@chapter Interaction

The interactive inspector (also known as the interactor) provides
a way to inspect a running vmips system without attaching a debugger.

You can enter the interactive inspector at any time while the 
simulation is running.
To enter the interactive inspector, hit Control-underscore (^_) which enters
an ASCII 0x1F (US) byte at the terminal. This will cause the
simulation to pause and the "vmips=>" interactor prompt to be
printed.

The interactor will loop prompting you for commands and processing
them until you enter a command that exits the interactor.

@section Command table

@table @samp
@item go
Continue execution and exit the interactive inspector.
You can reenter the interactive inspector again later by hitting
Control-underscore again.

@item step
Attempt to step one instruction.
After a single-step attempt, the PC will be printed.

@item halt
Halt machine, exit the interactive inspector, and quit VMIPS.

@item quit
Same as halt.

@item regs
Print the CPU registers.

@item cp0
Print the CP0 registers and TLB.

@item mem A
Print the first few words of memory starting from address A.  The address
provided must be a 32-bit, word-aligned address.

@item dis A
Disassemble the first few words of memory at address A.  The address
provided must be a 32-bit, word-aligned address.  Due to a limitation
in the current implementation, disassembly will invariably be printed
to standard error.

@item stack
Print the first few words of memory starting from the stack pointer.

@item help
