vmips-1.3 was released on 8 October 2004.
User-visible changes in version 1.3 (since version 1.2.2):

@itemize @bullet
@item The VMIPS code base has been cleaned up substantially. The most
important visible effect of this is that VMIPS compiles much more quickly now.

@item A new, experimental executable-file loader has been integrated. Presently
it is only usable for loading ECOFF files into the kernel segments
(0x80000000-0xbfffffff). The ROM monitor has a new @command{call} command you
can use to take advantage of this.

@item Vmipstool can now disassemble binary instructions from the command
line, e.g.  @samp{vmipstool --disassemble-word <pc> <instr>}.

@item The @option{excmsg} option used to report all exceptions, including
things like clock interrupts. This made using @option{excmsg} in any
nontrivial kernel code almost impossible. Now you must also specify
'reportirq' to get reports of interrupt exceptions.

@item The @option{haltjrra} option has been removed.

@item The DECstation 5000/200-compatible CSR device now supports delivery
of interrupts from devices attached to CSR interrupt lines, such as the DZ11
serial device.

@item The DZ11 serial device now supports interrupt-driven I/O properly. It
previously only worked correctly if polling was used.

@item The documentation has received the usual slight adjustments. In
addition, the test-suite documentation has been extensively revised and
integrated into the programmer's manual.

@item The options-processing code has been revised slightly to print a better
error message when an invalid option is specified.
@end itemize

vmips-1.2.2 was released on 23 August 2004.
User-visible changes in version 1.2.2 (since version 1.2.1):

@itemize @bullet
@item A bug in the Makefiles and configure scripts has been fixed, where
some files would not be installed if you didn't configure with cross
compilation tools (using @option{--with-mips}).

@item Vladimir Machulsky found and fixed a bug in the debugger interface,
where the register file would be sent to gdb incorrectly. Thanks!

@item VMIPS will no longer abort and dump core when bad command-line
rguments
are passed to it.  Instead, it will print an error message and exit with
a non-zero exit code.

@item A bug in the command-line option processor was fixed, where using a
completely empty @file{~/.vmipsrc} or the @samp{-F /dev/null} option could cause
the options parser to parse garbage, usually resulting in harmless,
but annoying error messages.
@end itemize

vmips-1.2.1 was released on 26 July 2004.
User-visible changes in version 1.2.1 (since version 1.2):

@itemize @bullet
@item Fixed a bug where delay slot execution could be triggered even when
emulating a malformed jr (jump-register) instruction.

@item Fixed a bug where, upon taking a TLB Miss exception, the ASID of the
page that could not be looked up would be overwritten (in the CP0 EntryHi
register) with garbage.

@item Fixed a bug in VMIPS configurations with multiple interrupt devices,
where Interrupt Pending bits of the CP0 Cause from previous interrupts could
be left asserted even if the device that asserted them had subsequently
deasserted them.

@item Fixed a bug where the memory dump file and ROM file would be opened
in text mode. They are now opened in binary mode.
@end itemize

vmips-1.2 was released on 26 June 2004.
User-visible changes in version 1.2 (since version 1.1.3):

@itemize @bullet
@item Many documentation updates have been made. Note that the documentation
has been relicensed under the MIT license, instead of the GNU FDL.

@item Many facets of VMIPS are now configurable at runtime, instead of at
compile time. For instance:

	It is now possible to build and install VMIPS without having previously
installed MIPS cross-compiler tools. In particular, VMIPS now incorporates
the portions of GNU libopcodes used to implement the MIPS disassembler,
so linking against an installed version of libopcodes from GNU binutils is
no longer necessary.

	It is now possible to switch the VMIPS CPU from big-endian to
little-endian mode or vice-versa using a command-line option.

	It is now possible to change the name of the configuration file
that VMIPS reads on startup using a command-line option. The @option{-o
configfile} option, which never worked, has been removed.

@item vmipstool now shares command-line processing code with vmips. It also
has a new --swap-words option that allows you to byteswap all the 4-byte
words in a file.

@item You can now specify numeric constants in command line options which
are multiples of 1024, 1024^2, or 1024^3 using the K, M, or G suffixes.

@item Several new emulated devices based on the DECstation 5000/200 have
been added.  In particular, it is no longer possible to disable the serial
device at compile time (or with @option{-o nousetty}), but you can choose
whether to use the DECstation serial chip or the SPIM-compatible serial
console (or neither) using new command-line options. In addition, the ROM
program distributed with VMIPS supports a "boot environment" similar to
that provided by the DECstation PROM. The new DECstation-compatible devices
have not been comprehensively validated; they should be considered "beta"
quality at this point.

@item There is a new tracing framework you can use to generate runtime
execution traces of programs that run in VMIPS. See the documentation of the
"tracing" command-line option and the other options that begin with "trace"
for more details.

@item The VMIPS interface to GDB now supports the "remote Z-packet" interface
for setting breakpoints.

@item VMIPS now prints more informative diagnostic messages about the causes
of bus errors and interrupts.

@item You can now use ^C (your terminal's Interrupt key) to stop VMIPS and
break into the debugger, if the @option{-o debug} command line option was
set, or ^\ (your terminal's Quit key) to halt VMIPS in an orderly manner at
any time.

@item The @option{--disable-debug} option to @code{configure} now strips the
compiled VMIPS binaries, although it has been documented to do this for some
time now.
@end itemize

